fields.title: What is CUET (UG)?
fields.text:
CUET (UG) stands for Common University Entrance Test UG. UG stands for Under Graduates.

CUET (UG) is a single window entrance test to seek admission, across the country, for any academic session, in any of the Central Universities (CUs) and other participating State Universities, Deemed Universities, and Private Universities.

In CUET (UG) 2022, 44 Central Universities (CUs), 12 State Universities, 13 Deemed Universities, and 21 Private Universities participated.

Candidates are admitted to their UG courses in the desired university based on the NTA Score secured in this test.

fields.title: What is NTA and its role in CUET (UG)?
fields.text:
NTA stands for the National Testing Agency (NTA). It is a premier, specialist, autonomous and self-sustained testing organization established by the Ministry of Education, MoE, to conduct entrance examinations for admission/fellowship in higher educational institutions.

NTA has been entrusted with the responsibility of conducting the CUET (UG).

The role of NTA is confined to the registration of candidates, issue of admit cards, conduct of exams, hosting answer keys and invite challenges, finalizing answer keys, process and declaring results.

Eligibility, reservation, admission, etc. are as per the rules and regulations of the respective participating university.

fields.title: How is CUET (UG) going to be helpful to a student?
fields.text:
In the past, students used to secure more than 95% marks in Class XII Board Examination to get admission to the University of their choice. The syllabus, standard of questions, marking scheme, and scoring pattern of different boards are different, so the same percentage in the separate board do not reflect the same academic performance of the student. Thus, admission based on the board exam marks does not justify the students.

With the introduction of CUET (UG), the selection process for the universities will now get standardized. The Common University Entrance Test CUET (UG) will provide a common platform and equal opportunity to all the candidates, across the country, irrespective of their boards. The testing and selection process becomes more uniform and democratic.

Moreover, the stress on students to secure very high marks in their respective board exams will also reduce.

fields.title: Is it compulsory for a candidate who desires to join any Central University to appear in CUET (UG)?
fields.text:
Yes. A candidate who wants admission in any UG courses in any Central University or its affiliated colleges for the academic year 2022-23 must appear in CUET (UG).

It has been mandated that admission to UG courses of Central Universities for the academic year 2022-23, will be done on the basis of the NTA Score obtained in CUET (UG).

fields.title: CUET - Gateway to Universities
fields.text:
The National Education Policy (NEP-2020) has elucidated that the entrance to Higher Education should be through Common Entrance Test at the national level so that there is a uniform standard of benchmarking of candidates.
The National Testing Agency (NTA) an autonomous testing organization established by the Ministry of Education, MoE has been entrusted to conduct entrance examinations for admission/fellowship in higher educational institutions.
In 2022, NTA conducts CUET (UG) 2022 for admission in 44 Central Universities (CUs), 12 State Universities, 13 Deemed Universities, and 21 Private Universities.
CUET (UG) is mandatory for admission in all Central Universities (CUs).
CUET (UG) is a computer-based test that will be conducted in 13 mediums across India to evaluate a student's competency for admission to universities for higher education.
Nearly 14.90 lac students appeared in the CUET (UG) 2022 exam for approximately 1.70 lac seats under different courses offered by 90 universities.

fields.title: CUET Sarthi - 100% Preparation, 100% Success
fields.text:
If getting enrolled in a prestigious university is your dream, then CUET- Sarthi is for you. We aim to provide democratized access to learn CUET-UG that opens your path to your dream university.

CUET, being one of the toughest competitive exams, needs ground-breaking strategy, focus, excellent study material, and proper guidance. We are the one-stop solution to provide you with the best of all. Being India’s largest and most dedicated learning platform CUET-UG, we offer to make you exam-ready with the help of qualified subject experts, the best study material, live and recorded video lectures, practice papers, mock test series, efficient doubt-solving sessions, and wide experience.

Our curriculum and course are so designed, paced, and integrated that the preparation of CUET (UG) goes hand in hand with Board Exam preparation and there is no extra pressure on the candidates to prepare for both exams. Preparation of CUET (UG) with our courses will rather help the candidates to prepare well for their Board Exams.

If you are a go-getter residing in rural or remote areas, metro or any tier city in India, then CUET - Sarthi help you to secure your seat in a premier higher education institution. You need not disturb your school curriculum and migrate from your town.

Let, your dream be our Goal, and begin with the Motto 100% Preparation, 100% Success !

fields.title: About CUET
fields.content:
Django is a powerful web framework that can help you get your Python application or website off the ground. Django includes a simplified development server for testing your code locally, but for anything even slightly production-related, a more secure and powerful web server is required.

In this guide, we will demonstrate how to install and configure some components on Ubuntu 20.04 to support and serve Django applications. We will be setting up a PostgreSQL database instead of using the default SQLite database. We will configure the Gunicorn application server to interface with our applications. We will then set up Nginx to reverse proxy to Gunicorn, giving us access to its security and performance features to serve our apps.

fields.course_description:
This course is meant for class 12th studying students. The course is crafted to give students complete preparation for the CUET (UG) 2022.

Under this course, students will get a hard copy text booklet, which contains theory, practice questions, and board exam practice exercises for each chapter.

This course is strongly recommended for students who aim to get admission to the desired course of their dream university. This course is designed to lay a solid foundation and understanding of the 12th Class Syllabus. It gives competitive exposure to students along with the preparation for board exams. It is so designed and paced, so as, not to create any burden for students in their school curriculum and Board exams preparation. Rather completing this course will help students to score better on their board exams.

Students can finish this course in 20 weeks devoting 1 Hour per day.
fields.paper_pattern: One question paper has 50 questions out of which 40 questions need to be attempted. All questions are objective type - Multiple-Choice Questions (MCQs) with only one correct option. Each question carries 5 marks.

fields.subject: accountancy
fields.syllabus_description:
Accounting for Not-for-Profit Organisations and Partnership Firms

Unit I: Accounting Not-for-Profit Organisation

  • Not-for-profit organization: Meaning and Examples.
  • Receipts and Payments: Meaning and Concept of fund-based and non-fund-based accounting.
  • Preparation of Income and Expenditure Account and Balance sheet from receipt and payment account with additional information.

Unit II: Accounting for Partnership

  • Nature of Partnership Firm: Partnership deed (meaning, importance).
  • Final Accounts of Partnership: Fixed v/s Fluctuating capital, Division of profit among partners, Profit, and Loss Appropriation account.

Unit III: Reconstitution of Partnership

Changes in profit sharing ratio among the existing partners – Sacrificing ratio and Gaining ratio.

  • Accounting for Revaluation of Assets and Liabilities and Distribution of reserves and accumulated profits.
  • Goodwill: Nature, Factors affecting and Methods of valuation: Average profit, Super profit, Multiplier, and Capitalisation methods.
  • Admission of a Partner: Effect of admission of a partner, Change in profit sharing ratio, the Accounting treatment for goodwill, Revaluation of assets and liabilities, Reserves (accumulated profits), and Adjustment of capital.
  • Retirement/Death of a Partner: Change in profit sharing ratio, Accounting treatment of goodwill, Revaluation of assets and liabilities, Adjustment of accumulated profits (Reserves).

Unit IV: Dissolution of Partnership Firm

  • Meaning, Settlement of accounts: Preparation of realization account and related accounts (excluding piecemeal distribution, sale to a company, and insolvency of a Partner)

Company Accounts and Financial Statement Analysis

Unit V: Accounting for Share and Debenture Capital

  • Share Capital: Meaning, Nature, and Types.
  • Accounting for Share Capital: Issue and Allotment of Equity and Preference Shares; Oversubscription and Under subscription; Issue at par, premium, and at discount; Calls in advance, Calls in arrears, Issue of shares for consideration other than cash.
  • Forfeiture of Shares: Accounting treatment, Re-issue of forfeited shares.
  • Presentation of shares and Debentures Capital in the company’s balance sheet.
  • Issue of Debenture – At par, premium, and discount; Issue of debentures for consideration other than cash.
  • Redemption of the debenture.
  • Out of proceeds of fresh issue, accumulated profits, and sinking fund.

Unit VI: Analysis of Financial Statements

  • Financial Statements of a Company: Preparation of simple financial statements of a company in the prescribed form with major headings only.
  • Financial Analysis: Meaning, Significance, Purpose, Limitations.
  • Tools for Financial Analysis: Comparative statements, Common size statements.
  • Accounting Ratios: Meaning and Objectives, Types of ratios:
  • Liquidity Ratios: The current ratio, Liquidity ratio.
    Solvency Ratio: Debt to equity, Total assets to debt, Proprietary ratio.
    Activity Ratio: Inventory turnover, Debtors turnover, Payables turnover, Working capital turnover, Fixed assets turnover, Current assets turnover.
    Profitability Ratio: Gross profit, Operating ratio, Net profit ratio, Return on Investment, Earning per Share, Dividend per Share, and Profit Earning ratio.

Unit VII: Statement of Changes in Financial Position

  • Cash Flow Statement: Meaning and Objectives, Preparation, Adjustments related to depreciation, dividend and tax, sale and purchase of non-current assets (as per revised standard issued by ICAI).

Computerized Accounting System

Unit I: Overview of Computerised Accounting System

  • Concept and Types of Computerised Accounting System (CAS).
  • Features of a Computerised Accounting System.
  • Structure of a Computerised Accounting System.

Unit II: Using Computerised Accounting System

  • Steps in the installation of CAS, Preparation of chart of accounts, Codification, and Hierarchy of account heads.
  • Data entry, Data validation, and Data verification.
  • Adjusting entries, Preparation of financial statements, Closing entries and Opening entries.
  • Security of CAS and Security features are generally available in CAS (Students are expected to understand and practice the entire accounting process using an accounting package.)

Unit III: Accounting Using Database Management System (DBMS)

  • Concepts of DBMS.Objects in DBMS: Tables, Queries, Forms, Reports.
  • Creating data tables for accounting.
  • Using queries, forms, and reports for generating accounting information. Applications of DBMS in generating accounting information such as shareholders’ records, sales reports, customers’ profiles, suppliers’ profiles payroll, employees’ profiles, and petty cash registers.

Unit IV: Accounting Applications of Electronic Spreadsheet

  • Concept of an Electronic Spreadsheet (ES).
  • Features offered by Electronic Spreadsheet.
  • Applications of Electronic Spreadsheet in generating accounting information, preparing depreciation schedules, loan repayment schedules, payroll accounting, and other such companies

fields.subject: languages_ia_ib
fields.syllabus_description:
Section IA Languages (13):

English, Hindi, Assamese, Bengali, Gujarati, Kannada, Malayalam, Marathi, Odia, Punjabi, Tamil, Telugu, Urdu

Section IB Languages (20):

Arabic, Bodo, Chinese, Dogri, French, German, Italian, Japanese, Kashmiri, Konkani, Maithili, Manipuri, Nepali,
Persian, Russian, Santhali, Sindhi, Spanish, Tibetan, Sanskrit,

Syllabus:

  • Reading Comprehension:
    There will be three types of passages (maximum 300-350 words):
    • Factual
    • Narrative
    • Literary
  • Verbal Ability
  • Rearranging the parts
  • Choosing the correct word
  • Synonyms and Antonyms
  • Vocabulary

fields.subject: general_test
fields.syllabus_description:
The Question Paper will contain questions from the following topics :

General Knowledge, Current Affairs, General Mental Ability, Numerical Ability, Quantitative Reasoning (Simple application of basic mathematical concepts arithmetic/algebra geometry/mensuration/statistics taught till Grade 8), Logical and Analytical Reasoning.
